12:15.001 --> 12:18.002
I want that
weather punk gone!

12:18.004 --> 12:21.339
I just heard
you got Memphis fired.

12:21.341 --> 12:23.608
He was deadweight,
ratings poison,

12:23.610 --> 12:25.410
a real Ray Donovan.

12:25.412 --> 12:27.011
I was looking out
for ya.

12:27.013 --> 12:29.447
Look, you've been such
a good friend to me,

12:29.449 --> 12:31.716
so speaking
as your good friend,

12:31.718 --> 12:33.518
I think your love
of the limelight

12:33.520 --> 12:35.019
is clouding
your judgment.

12:35.021 --> 12:36.921
Oh. Wow!

12:36.923 --> 12:39.257
Thank you
for helping me realize

12:39.259 --> 12:41.559
(crunch)
what an ingrate you are.

12:41.561 --> 12:43.061
Francine,
you're hurting me!

12:43.063 --> 12:44.562
<i> I</i> get the viewers.

12:44.564 --> 12:46.564
<i>I</i> make the news fun.
(crunch)

12:46.566 --> 12:48.933
And I do it all
to help<i> you!</i>

12:48.935 --> 12:50.135
Well, you're gonna have
a hard time

12:50.137 --> 12:52.637
helping me,
because me quits!

12:52.639 --> 12:53.738
(sobbing)

12:53.740 --> 12:55.073
wait, wait!

12:55.075 --> 12:56.541
Greg, come back!

12:56.543 --> 12:58.910
I didn't mean
what I said.

12:58.912 --> 13:01.279
I've never seen
"Ray Donovan."

13:01.281 --> 13:03.081
It could be
a good show.

13:03.083 --> 13:05.650
I don't know.
We don't get Showtime.

13:05.652 --> 13:07.218
Everything else
I said stands.

13:07.220 --> 13:08.953
(sobbing)

13:14.327 --> 13:17.095
Stupid, ungrateful Greg.

13:17.097 --> 13:19.898
I guess some friends just
don't want to be helped.

13:39.953 --> 13:41.820
Oh, my God!

13:41.822 --> 13:45.089
I was so busy telling myself
I was helping Greg,

13:45.091 --> 13:47.458
I couldn't see how much
I was hurting him.

13:47.460 --> 13:49.794
Oh, we need
to make this right.

13:49.796 --> 13:52.664
Are you okay, losing
your Loco Larry's perks?

13:52.666 --> 13:54.632
Hey, helping Greg
is more important

13:54.634 --> 13:56.434
than eating
16 burritos a day,

13:56.436 --> 13:57.635
every day of the week.

13:57.637 --> 13:58.837
Also, my --

13:58.839 --> 14:00.038
my colon came out.

14:00.040 --> 14:01.139
What?

14:01.141 --> 14:02.507
M-my colon came out.

14:02.509 --> 14:04.509
I-I looked it up online
and it is reversible.

14:04.511 --> 14:08.179
Greg and Memphis are so clearly
right for each other.

14:08.181 --> 14:10.815
We need to get 'em
back together

14:10.817 --> 14:12.450
<i> and</i> back on the air.

14:12.452 --> 14:15.453
Easier said than done.
Mmm. Mmm.

14:15.455 --> 14:17.522
Greg's done with TV.
Runs a cake shop now.

14:17.524 --> 14:20.491
Another interesting tidbit --
Greg might not be

14:20.493 --> 14:23.595
the macho lady-killer
we all think he is.

14:27.901 --> 14:29.567
Greg, please.

14:29.569 --> 14:32.570
You're the one who belongs
behind that desk, not me.

14:32.572 --> 14:34.572
I'm sorry.
I'm not going back.

14:34.574 --> 14:36.541
Even if you did get
Memphis back, too.

14:36.543 --> 14:38.176
And good luck with<i> that.</i>

14:38.178 --> 14:39.577
He's a stormchaser now.

14:39.579 --> 14:41.145
Said at least
you can trust a tornado

14:41.147 --> 14:42.981
not to stab you in the back.

14:42.983 --> 14:44.983
Also, you know Ashley in HR?

14:44.985 --> 14:47.151
Got an abortion.

14:47.153 --> 14:49.721
What do we need
a weatherman for anyway?

14:49.723 --> 14:51.322
You said it yourself.

14:51.324 --> 14:52.557
Unless, of course,
there was some sort of

14:52.559 --> 14:54.926
cataclysmic superstorm
to cover.

14:54.928 --> 14:58.062
But barring that, I would
get rid of the snake room

14:58.064 --> 14:59.764
before I brought back
Greg and Memphis.

14:59.766 --> 15:01.866
Ohh!

15:01.868 --> 15:04.068
(munching)

15:04.070 --> 15:05.937
I just know deep down,

15:05.939 --> 15:08.039
Greg wants to come back
to the news.

15:08.041 --> 15:10.575
If I could only get
him and Memphis back

15:10.577 --> 15:13.177
on the air together
for one broadcast.

15:13.179 --> 15:14.579
But we'd need to be able

15:14.581 --> 15:16.547
to control the weather
to do that.

15:16.549 --> 15:19.517
Easy as pie.

15:19.519 --> 15:21.552
Stan, that's a cake.
-Oh, what would you say?

15:21.554 --> 15:22.754
"Piece of cake."

15:22.756 --> 15:24.022
Oh, yeah,
it's really easy

15:24.024 --> 15:25.356
to come up
with clever word play

15:25.358 --> 15:26.691
when you're not
holding in your butthole

15:26.693 --> 15:28.192
with a piece
of duct tape.

15:28.194 --> 15:29.794
(ring)

15:29.796 --> 15:32.530
Top-secret CIA weather-control
division. Dick speaking.

15:32.532 --> 15:34.098
I mean, pizza store!

15:34.100 --> 15:35.633
Oh, it's you, Stan.

15:35.635 --> 15:37.101
What kind of favor?

15:43.610 --> 15:44.809
(warble)

15:52.786 --> 15:54.619
(playing heavy metal)

15:54.621 --> 15:57.188
(thunder rumbles)

15:59.626 --> 16:02.126
(doorbell rings)

16:02.128 --> 16:03.328
(gasps)

16:03.330 --> 16:04.629
can I help you?

16:04.631 --> 16:06.731
You've aged beautifully.

16:06.733 --> 16:07.932
What?
-A drink? Sure!

16:07.934 --> 16:09.334
I'll take a sweet tea,
no ice.

16:09.336 --> 16:11.002
You'll have one, too.
Put this in yours.

16:11.004 --> 16:13.504
Come on in. Let's get you
out of those wet clothes.

16:13.506 --> 16:16.074
(wind blows)

16:19.145 --> 16:21.079
Hello?
I received an order

16:21.081 --> 16:22.780
to deliver a cake
to this lamppost.

16:22.782 --> 16:24.315
(tires screech)

16:24.317 --> 16:26.150
I got a call saying
my birth mother

16:26.152 --> 16:27.986
would meet me
at this lamppost.

16:27.988 --> 16:29.153
Greg?

16:29.155 --> 16:31.422
Memphis?
(thunder rumbles)

16:31.424 --> 16:34.659
Oh, my God, a category-6
subpolar tornado-cane,

16:34.661 --> 16:36.661
the rarest storm
in all of weather!

16:36.663 --> 16:39.097
Don't tell us,
tell the viewers.

16:39.099 --> 16:41.366
Our breaking story right now --

16:41.368 --> 16:45.503
a weather event that I couldn't
even<i> begin</i> to explain.

16:45.505 --> 16:46.971
Oh!

16:46.973 --> 16:48.940
So we're going to go live
to Greg Corbin

16:48.942 --> 16:52.477
and Memphis Stormfront,
in the heart of the storm.

16:52.479 --> 16:54.512
Ohhh?!

16:54.514 --> 16:56.347
I told you, I'm done
with the news, Stan.

16:56.349 --> 16:57.815
I'm a cake man now!

16:57.817 --> 16:59.450
You're a what?

16:59.452 --> 17:00.618
(thunder rumbles)

17:00.620 --> 17:02.153
Goddamn it,
I'm a news man!

17:02.155 --> 17:03.621
Greg Corbin, here,

17:03.623 --> 17:05.623
live in the midst
of the storm of the century,

17:05.625 --> 17:07.859
with our very own
Memphis Stormfront.

17:07.861 --> 17:10.495
Greg, we are witnessing
a once-in-a-lifetime

17:10.497 --> 17:14.065
weather event unleashing
multiple funnel clouds.

17:17.470 --> 17:19.537
The gators
are gettin' spooked!

17:19.539 --> 17:22.006
Get 'em into the barn,
and quick!

17:22.008 --> 17:23.307
Hyah!

17:23.309 --> 17:25.043
It's too late!

17:25.045 --> 17:28.146
(growling)

17:28.148 --> 17:30.982
(lightning crackles)

17:30.984 --> 17:32.850
(alarm blares)

17:32.852 --> 17:34.419
(people screaming)

17:34.421 --> 17:36.154
In a stunning development,

17:36.156 --> 17:39.924
we are now in the midst
of a full-fledged gator storm.

17:39.926 --> 17:41.793
(cheering)

17:43.396 --> 17:44.729
Aah!

17:48.168 --> 17:49.600
(gasping)

17:49.602 --> 17:50.768
Aah!

17:50.770 --> 17:52.236
(whimpering)

17:54.007 --> 17:56.074
(sighs)

17:56.076 --> 17:58.743
(hissing, rattling)

17:58.745 --> 18:00.545
(blows)

18:00.547 --> 18:03.047
By the way, great to be back on
the air with you, Memphis.

18:03.049 --> 18:04.382
What have you been
up to lately?

18:04.384 --> 18:07.051
Well, I finally caught
"Step Up: All in"

18:07.053 --> 18:08.753
on cable this weekend.

18:08.755 --> 18:10.688
That mess?
They should've --

18:10.690 --> 18:13.224
(gasps)
called it "Throw Up: All over."

18:13.226 --> 18:15.560
They<i> should've</i>
called it off.

18:15.562 --> 18:17.462
(laughs)

18:17.464 --> 18:21.365
Even in the belly of the storm,
they banter flawlessly.

18:21.367 --> 18:23.601
These are my stars!

18:26.973 --> 18:29.474
(gulping)

18:29.476 --> 18:33.077
Ahh!

18:33.079 --> 18:35.379
You know, you look
familiar to me.

18:35.381 --> 18:38.216
I did do a bit
of board-game modeling,

18:38.218 --> 18:39.750
back in my younger days.

18:39.752 --> 18:40.985
Oh, yeah,
maybe that's it.

18:40.987 --> 18:42.086
I think I --
I think I remember.

18:42.088 --> 18:43.788
Was it, um...

18:43.790 --> 18:45.156
Oh, God, it's
on the tip of my --

18:45.158 --> 18:47.325
I want to say
mystery phone?

18:47.327 --> 18:48.626
Dream Phone.
-Dream Phone, Dream Phone.

18:48.628 --> 18:49.894
Right. Now I remember.
It's been --

18:49.896 --> 18:51.329
been such a long time.

18:51.331 --> 18:53.264
Is that the phone
from the game

18:53.266 --> 18:54.732
that you're holding
right now?

18:54.734 --> 18:56.567
So, it is.

18:56.569 --> 18:58.136
Say, you know,
I got the day free.

18:58.138 --> 18:59.670
What do you say
we head to the mall

18:59.672 --> 19:01.839
and grab ourselves
a slice of 'za?

19:01.841 --> 19:06.244
Ugh! I try to stay away
from malls and pizza.

19:06.246 --> 19:08.946
I'm beginning to get
the distinct impression,

19:08.948 --> 19:11.782
Dylan,
that you are a liar.

19:11.784 --> 19:14.352
Well, I wouldn't exactly
call it lying,

19:14.354 --> 19:18.022
but for starters,
my name's not actually Dylan.

19:20.793 --> 19:24.462
So, um,
what happened back there?

19:24.464 --> 19:26.164
We went to the mall
and had pizza,

19:26.166 --> 19:29.133
because that's
what Dylan likes.

19:29.135 --> 19:31.435
Why is there blood
on the Dream Phone?

19:31.437 --> 19:33.304
He likes malls
and pizza...

19:33.306 --> 19:34.438
and me.

19:38.444 --> 19:40.311
Roger?

19:40.313 --> 19:41.846
W-what's in this jar?

19:41.848 --> 19:45.950
Dylan was being bad,
and now we have the jar.

19:45.952 --> 19:48.553
<i> ¶ I'm so excited ¶</i>

19:48.555 --> 19:51.422
<i> ¶ And I just can't hide it ¶</i>

19:56.829 --> 20:00.064
Well, it's official --
I'm out at channel 3

20:00.066 --> 20:03.401
and you two are back in,
thanks to us.

20:03.403 --> 20:04.635
What do you mean,
thanks to you?

20:04.637 --> 20:06.170
We did all of this.

20:06.172 --> 20:07.705
Francine got you on the air,

20:07.707 --> 20:10.474
and I abused my CIA powers
to make that superstorm.

20:10.476 --> 20:13.211
You<i> made</i> this storm?

20:13.213 --> 20:15.346
Lives were destroyed.

20:15.348 --> 20:18.349
But<i> Greg's</i> life
was fixed.

20:18.351 --> 20:20.518
Now you've got
a new work partner

20:20.520 --> 20:23.221
<i>and</i> a new life partner.

20:23.223 --> 20:25.056
Now kiss,
you two lovebirds.

20:25.058 --> 20:26.224
And put some mustard on it.

20:28.761 --> 20:30.361
Aren't you straight?

20:30.363 --> 20:32.730
Yes, but I'm terrified
of these people.

20:32.732 --> 20:34.932
They can control
the weather!

20:34.934 --> 20:37.001
BOTH: Mmm.

20:40.340 --> 20:42.373
You did it, baby.

20:42.375 --> 20:43.608
<i> We</i> did it.

20:43.610 --> 20:45.209
Because<i> we're</i> helpers.

20:45.211 --> 20:46.877
It's just in our nature.

20:46.879 --> 20:48.512
We help.

20:51.751 --> 20:53.618
Mommy?

20:57.290 --> 20:59.423
(growls)

21:02.128 --> 21:04.161
Bye!
Have a beautiful time!
